{"key":"processedPost-19844803","value":{"id":19844803,"first":19844514,"last":19849340,"when":1397518515,"utime":"04/15/14 02:35 AM","content":"There's no need for bad advice.&nbsp; Casing layers should be applied either when the substrate is first made, or right at full colonization when the cover is removed.&nbsp; Never allow contaminants to fall for any period of time on a substrate and then add a casing layer.<br />I don't want to hear that 'so and so' did it and it was fine.&nbsp; It's bad practice and will fail too often.<br />To the OP, you should say 'what' the substrate and proposed casing layer will be.&nbsp; 3\" isn't very thick for straw but it's near the point of diminishing returns for manure. Two 2\" substrates will produce far more than a single 4\" thick substrate.<br />RR","title":"Re: depth"}}